To find the points of intersection, we can substitute the first equation into the second.  This gives us
\[x + 4 = ((x + 1)^2 - 3)^2.\]Expanding, we get
\[x + 4 = x^4 + 4x^3 + 2x^2 - 8x - 8.\]This simplifies to $x^4 + 4x^3 + 2x^2 - 9x - 12 = 0.$  We can factor this as $(x + 2)^2 (x^2 + 1) = 0,$ so $x = -2.$

Substituting $x = -2$ into $y = (x + 1)^2,$ we get $y = 1.$  Thus, the intersection points are $(-2,1)$ and $(1,-2).$  The other two intersection points are the reflections of these points across the line $y = x,$ which are $(1,-2)$ and $(-2,1).$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair moo (real t) {
  return((t + 1)^2,t);
}

pair foo (real t) {
  return(t,(t + 3)^2 - 4);
}

path foograph = foo(-5);
real t;

for (t = -5; t <= 2; t = t + 0.1) {
  foograph = foograph--foo(t);
}

path moograph = moo(-3);

for (t = -3; t <= 2; t = t + 0.1) {
  moograph = moograph--moo(t);
}

draw(foograph,red);
draw(moograph,blue);
draw((-5,0)--(3,0));
draw((0,-5)--(0,3));

dot("$(-2,1)$", (-2,1), NW);
dot("$(1,-2)$", (1,-2), SE);
[/asy]

Let $O$ be the center of the circle.  Since the circle passes through $(-2,1)$ and $(1,-2),$ the midpoint of $\overline{(-2,1)(1,-2)},$ which is $\left( -\frac{1}{2}, -\frac{1}{2} \right),$ lies on the perpendicular bisector of $\overline{(-2,1)(1,-2)}.$

